                                <p><hi rend="initialcap">C</hi>ASE 167.—<name type="person" key="702">Private Everett H.
                                                Felton</name>, <name type="organization" key="694">Co. G, 187th Pa.</name>; age 28; was admitted <date type="admit" when="1864-08-30">Aug. 30, 1864</date>,
                                        with an apparently mild attack of typhoid fever; but on
                                        <date type="injury" when="1864-09-20">September 20</date> a profuse diarrhœa supervened, and he
                                        died <date type="death" when="1864-10-05">October 5</date>.  <hi rend="italic">Post-mortem</hi> examination <date type="autopsy" when="1864-10-05">ten hours after death</date>: Body much emaciated. Brain and thoracic
                                        viscera normal; a fibrinous clot in each side of the heart;
                                        spleen and kidneys normal; several Peyer's patches and
                                        solitary follicles ulcerated; numerous small ulcers in the
                                        large intestine.—<hi rend="italic"><name type="person" key="246">Act. Ass't Surg. H. M.
                                                  Dean</name>, <name type="hospital" key="176">Lincoln Hospital</name>, Washington, D. C.</hi></p>                        
